===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|辛|斤|c1=p|c2=s|ls=psc}} — to chop wood. Original form of {{och-l|薪|gloss=firewood}}. The character was later borrowed to represent {{och-l|新|new}} as an instance of {{liushu|j|nocap=y}}.

A semantic {{och-l|*木}} was later added in the bronze inscriptions which merged with the {{och-l|*辛}}.

''{{w|Shuowen}}'' misinterprets the character as {{och-l|*𣓀}} + {{och-l|*斤}}.

===Etymology===
Sino-Tibetan; cognate with {{cog|my|သစ်||new}}. Compare the cognacy between {{och-l|薪|firewood}} and {{cog|my|သစ်||wood; timber}}.

This word may belong to the Sino-Tibetan stem {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*sreŋ||alive, fresh, green}} and may hence be related to {{och-l|青|gloss=green}} as well as {{och-l|薪|gloss=firewood}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

